06831nam a22010815i 9783110216110DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20092009gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)719448495  a97831102161107 a10.1515/97831102161102doi  a(DE-B1597)36138  a(OCoLC)436620533  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPD380b.I54 2009 7aLAN0090002bisacsh0481ua430.045qDE-101222/ger00aInformation Structure and Language Change :bNew Approaches to Word Order Variation in Germanic /ced. by Roland Hinterhölzl, Svetlana Petrova. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (394 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v2030 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe volume presents new approaches to explaining word order variation and change in the Germanic languages and thus relates to one of the most prominent and widely discussed topics in the theory of language change and diachronic syntax. The novelty of our approach consists in three main points. First of all, we aim at describing functional variety in the field of word order and verb placement in the early Germanic languages not as a result of language contact, but rather as a language-internal phenomenon related to stylistic and grammatical conditions in information packaging. Second, given that information structure is not directly accessible in texts from historical corpora that are available only in written form and bear no or little information on prosody and intonation, it presents various methods of retrieving information-structural categories in such texts. Third, it presents empirical studies on the relation between word order and information structure of the four main texts of the Old High German period and embeds these results in the wider picture of word order change in Germanic. The volume will be of interest to students of German, English, and general linguistics as well as to researchers interested in diachronic syntax, philology of Older German, language change, information structure, discourse semantics, language typology, computational linguistics, and corpus studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGermanic languagesxSyntax. 0aGermanic languagesxWord order. 4aGermanische Völker /Sprachen. 4aSprachgeschichte. 4aSyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aHistorical linguistics.  agermanic languages.  asyntax.1 aAxel, Katrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleischer, Jürg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinterhölzl, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinterhölzl, Roland, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHróarsdóttir, Þorbjörg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemenade, Ans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrisch, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinde, Sonja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLötscher, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLühr, Rosemarie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetrova, Svetlana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetrova, Svetlana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchlachter, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSolf, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyte